I saved the raw RT (steps) and x/y coordinates for
each simulation in the above .1->.6 files. You can filter
out all 18000 simulations by grepping out the files with
the string 'RES' in them.

See 
howto4roger/tacc_stampede.txt
howto4roger/openmpi_build.txt
...for running simulations using benchtwod3.f on one node
(one node has 68 cores, 4 threads per core)

In order to use more than one node, we needed to add in MPI
to pass values from accum in nodes back to a master node.
The program to do this is a modified version of
benchtwod3.f called benchtwod3mpi.f

We are still using openMP to distribute threads to cores
on each node. Note that I did not try to minimize calls
to random number generators to fractions of nsim, even
though the parallel sections are scaled down by the number
of cores (nsim/N threads per accum execution per node).

MPI runs all of benchtwod3mpi.f on all nodes, except 
for areas surrounded by IF statements which are relegated
to the "master". Again, I did not take exacting care to
make sure that the non-master nodes were doing less work 
than they needed to. It really doesn't matter: those non-
master nodes simply pass their accum results to the master,
and then they do whatever they want. All I did was make 
sure they did not print out messages, which would confuse
the output.

The critical MPI commands are MPI_SEND (which sends accum results
from non-master nodes) and MPI_RECV (which the master issues and
waits on each non-master node in turn for its MPI_SEND). The
master then places the received data into arrays and continues
with the processing, calculating quantiles, etc.

Compile benchtwod3mpi.f like this on Stampede:

(We still need mkl_dfti.o, but don't need to make it with mpiifort.)

ifort -ipo -c /opt/intel/Compiler/11.1/064/mkl/include/mkl_dfti.f90

mpiifort -traceback -xMIC-AVX512 -qopenmp -lmkl_intel_lp64 \
-lmkl_intel_thread -lmkl_core benchtwod3mpi.f mkl_dfti.o -o benchtwod3mpi

In order to run MPI prograns you must submit them using
sbatch. (srun errors-out).

sbatch takes a batch file which looks like this:

mpi.batchfile
-------
#!/bin/bash
#SBATCH -J myMPI           # job name
#SBATCH -o myMPI.o%j       # output and error file name (%j expands to jobID)
#SBATCH -n 6               # total number of mpi tasks requested
#SBATCH -N 6               # total number of nodes requested
#SBATCH -p normal          # queue (partition) -- normal, development, etc.
#SBATCH -t 01:30:00        # run time (hh:mm:ss) - 1.5 hours
#SBATCH --mail-user=russchilders@gmail.com
#SBATCH --mail-type=begin  # email me when the job starts
#SBATCH --mail-type=end    # email me when the job finishes

export OMP_NUM_THREADS=64
#export KMP_AFFINITY="verbose,compact"
export KMP_AFFINITY="compact"
export KMP_HW_SUBSET=1T,1O

ibrun ./benchtwod3mpi        # run the MPI executable
-------

The lines 
#SBATCH -n 6               # total number of mpi tasks requested
#SBATCH -N 6               # total number of nodes requested
...tell the batch processor to use 6 nodes and to run one version
of ./benchtwod3mpi on each.

Note that we were in the $WORK directory
/work/04601/tg839007/benchtwod3
on the KNL Cluster.

Run the batch file like this:

sbatch --cpu-freq=high mpi.batchfile

