To run this on eccles:

ifort -c /opt/intel/Compiler/11.1/064/mkl/include/mkl_dfti.f90

/tmp/bin/mpifort -O3 -tpp7 -xW -cm -no-prec-div -w -openmp \
-L/opt/intel/Compiler/11.1/064/mkl/lib/em64t -lmkl_intel_lp64 \
-lmkl_intel_thread -lmkl_core \
-I/opt/intel/composer_xe_2015.0.090/mkl/include \
benchtwod3mpi.f mkl_dfti.o -o benchtwod3mpi

Note that the "-ipo" flag is excluded, because that created errors
on eccles.

Compile the reality check program russ2.f:

/tmp/bin/mpifort russ2.f -o russ2

Run russ2 on eccles and core64rr

/tmp/bin/mpirun -x LD_LIBRARY_PATH -host eccles,core64rr -np 2 ./russ2

--> Note that we have to export the LD_LIBRARY_PATH (to core64rr)

Run on core64rr only (from core64rr):

/tmp/bin/mpirun --bind-to none ./benchtwod3mpi

/tmp/bin/mpirun -x LD_LIBRARY_PATH -x OMP_NUM_THREADS=64 -host core64rr -n 1 benchtwod3mpi

Run on eccles,core64rr,core48 (from eccles):

/tmp/bin/mpirun --bind-to none -x LD_LIBRARY_PATH -x OMP_NUM_THREADS=64 -host eccles,core64rr,core48 -n 3 ./benchtwod3mpi

Note that "--bind-to none" is included to allow threaded processes to go to 
the nodes they want.

January 13, 2017
================

Created a new MPI benchtwod3mpi.f:

benchtwod3mpi.f.new_accum.f

...which keeps the "slave" routines inside of accum.
The "master" sends parameters to the "slaves", accumulates
the results, and then sends more parameters. The "master"
tells the "slaves" to exit by sending a ter=-1 to them.

Had trouble at first getting the "master" to send parameters
to the "slaves". Ends up that this is solved by having "slaves"
initially send a dummy message to the "master". After that,
back-and-forth communication works fine.

