My reply:

Look at

/u/russ/bench/intel/benchtwod3/benchtwod3mpi.f.new_accum.f

The MPI-specific calls are at the top and bottom of the main routine
and inside of accum(). Note that I declare dummy parameters at the
start of the program for the first call the slaves make to accum() [I
call ter terL, for "local", but it could be ter and it won't hurt
anything. We need the individual parameters in the dummy call because
accum() doesn't like it if you call it without the correct variable
types and sizes). The final message to the slaves has a terL=-1, to
tell them to exit.

Note the

include "mpif.h"

line, which is needed in the main routine and in accum(). This has
variable, structure, and subroutine declarations. Probably paths as
well.

I put reality-check print statements "I am IRANK" to report if a node
is the master (IRANK of zero) or a slave (IRANK of 1,2,...). Those can
be commented out after things are running.

You can try out your routine locally by compiling it with this:

ifort -c /opt/intel/Compiler/11.1/064/mkl/include/mkl_dfti.f90

/tmp/bin/mpifort -O3 -tpp7 -xW -cm -no-prec-div -w -openmp \
-L/opt/intel/Compiler/11.1/064/mkl/lib/em64t -lmkl_intel_lp64 \
-lmkl_intel_thread -lmkl_core \
-I/opt/intel/composer_xe_2015.0.090/mkl/include \
<your routine name here> mkl_dfti.o -o twod3parallelmpi

Then running it with this:

/tmp/bin/mpirun --bind-to none -x LD_LIBRARY_PATH -x
OMP_NUM_THREADS=64 -host eccles,core64rr,core48 -n 3
./twod3parallelmpi

Note that I removed the -ipo flag, because it was causing compiler
errors on eccles.

